  <!-- ===================== STRUCTURAL KILLS ===================== -->

  <div class="panel" id="panel-fatal-structural">
    <div class="section-header"><div class="bar amber"></div> Structural Fatal Zones</div>
    <p class="section-sub">System architecture, data pipelines, and platform dependencies. These are engineering failures — the rivets, engines, and fuel lines. When they fail, the aircraft breaks apart.</p>

```
<div class="card-grid">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon amber">🎯</div><div class="card-title">Cockpit — Governance & Key-Person Risk</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>The single fund accountant who "just knows"</strong> how Fund X works. No documentation, no cross-training, no playbook. When they leave, the institutional knowledge evaporates overnight. Pricing committee decisions held in someone's head. Approval chains that exist only as convention. The cockpit is where silent, catastrophic loss happens.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon amber">⚡</div><div class="card-title">Left Engine — Data Lineage & Source Truth</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>Everyone watches the NAV output. Nobody traces the input.</strong> A price feed silently switches from bid to mid. A counterparty changes their SWIFT format. A static data field drifts. By the time this shows up as a NAV break, you've been wrong for weeks. The data lineage chain has no circuit breaker — it fails silently and propagates forward.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon amber">⚖️</div><div class="card-title">Right Engine — Regulatory Interpretation</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>AIFMD II, SFDR, CBI reporting — you can be technically compliant and substantively wrong.</strong> The reg text says one thing; the CBI guidance note says another; industry practice has drifted to a third. The classification logic, the SFDR Article 8/9 boundary, the QIAIF investment limit interpretation — judgment calls embedded in code nobody reviews until an inspection letter arrives.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon amber">🔗</div><div class="card-title">Fuel Line — Cash & Position Recon Chain</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>The invisible pipeline connecting custodian, TA, and accounting.</strong> A failed SWIFT message. A settlement instruction that aged out. A cash account that reconciled to zero because both sides were wrong by the same amount. Breaks here are asymmetric: cheap to prevent, catastrophic to fix retrospectively.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon amber">🔌</div><div class="card-title">Wing Root (L) — Integration Seams</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>Where the TA platform meets the accounting engine meets the pricing source.</strong> Each system works. The integration between them doesn't — or works differently on month-end vs. daily cycle. Timezone mismatches, batch sequencing dependencies, race conditions on concurrent NAV runs. The seam accumulates structural fatigue invisibly until a complex event snaps it.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon amber">🏭</div><div class="card-title">Wing Root (R) — Vendor Dependency & Lock-in</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>The platform vendor owns your data model.</strong> Your NAV calculation logic lives in their proprietary format. Your regulatory configuration is in their schema. When they deprecate a module, raise prices 40%, or get acquired — you don't have a migration path. You have a hostage negotiation.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon amber">✈️</div><div class="card-title">Tail Join — Operational Continuity</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>What happens when three people resign in the same quarter?</strong> When the BCP is tested — not the documented one, the real one? When the outsource partner's outsource partner has a production incident? Most fund accounting products have never been tested at their actual failure boundary, only at the boundary they designed for.</div>
  </div>
</div>
```

  </div>

  <!-- ===================== HUMAN KILLS ===================== -->

  <div class="panel" id="panel-fatal-human">
    <div class="section-header"><div class="bar purple"></div> Human & Cultural Fatal Zones</div>
    <p class="section-sub">The failure modes that don't show up in any system log. These live in the gap between what people know and what the platform captures — in the culture, the morale, and the institutional memory.</p>

```
<div class="card-grid">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon purple">🧠</div><div class="card-title">The "Why" Gap — Institutional Memory Loss</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>As platforms automate standard NAV calculations, can your staff still manually audit a complex performance fee waterfall?</strong> Regulators increasingly scrutinise whether firms retain the expertise to oversee and override automated systems — "take-back testing" capability. If the system does the thinking and nobody remembers how to check it, the automation isn't a safety net. It's a blindfold.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon purple">🪦</div><div class="card-title">The Excel Graveyard — Shadow IT</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>How many critical processes are held together by a macro built by one mid-level analyst?</strong> These manual interventions are invisible to senior management but will instantly break your daily deliverables when that employee takes holiday or resigns. The Excel graveyard is the shadow load-bearing structure — it looks like a workaround but it's actually your production system.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon purple">🔇</div><div class="card-title">Psychological Safety — The Near-Miss Silence</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>If you're seeing a surprisingly low number of reported near-misses, it is rarely a sign of a flawless system.</strong> It's usually an indicator of a culture of fear, where staff are quietly covering up mistakes rather than fixing root causes. In aviation, near-miss reporting is the single most valuable safety signal. In fund administration, it's the signal most likely to be suppressed.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon purple">🔥</div><div class="card-title">Data Pipeline Burnout — The Talent Drain</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>How much time do your highly paid accounting staff spend cleaning messy data or manually handling third-party feed exceptions?</strong> This fragmentation is a primary driver of burnout, pushing top talent out and leaving behind those content to simply click buttons. The people who leave aren't the problem — they're the canary. The problem is the environment that made them leave.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon purple">🤖</div><div class="card-title">Rubber-Stamping — Functional Illiteracy</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>With highly automated regulatory reporting, are your reviewers genuinely analysing outputs for anomalies — or just approving because the software has historically been accurate?</strong> This is the Wald principle in microcosm: the report has always been correct, so nobody checks it, so when it's wrong, nobody catches it. The automation created a new failure mode: the atrophy of the human override.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon purple">🚪</div><div class="card-title">Service Erosion — The Revolving Door Cost</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>Standard HR metrics track recruitment cost (50-150% of salary). They don't track service erosion</strong> — the frustration clients experience when they have to re-explain their processes and nuances to a revolving door of new, functionally inexperienced staff. Each handover creates a window where the new person doesn't know what they don't know. The client does. That's the beginning of the RFP process.</div>
  </div>
</div>
```

  </div>

  <!-- ===================== VISIBLE HITS ===================== -->

  <div class="panel" id="panel-visible">
    <div class="section-header"><div class="bar red"></div> Where the Bullet Holes Are</div>
    <p class="section-sub">These are the problems everyone can see — and where the industry spends most of its armour budget. Important, but survivable. The product gets hit here and keeps flying.</p>

```
<div class="card-grid">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon red">📊</div><div class="card-title">NAV Calculation Accuracy</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Heavily tested, heavily automated. Tolerance checks, dual pricing, independent verification. Every platform invests here because it's measurable, visible, and auditable. A NAV error is embarrassing — but it's caught, corrected, and reported. <strong>This is the most armoured part of the aircraft.</strong></div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon red">📋</div><div class="card-title">Regulatory Filing Deadlines</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Filing calendars, automated reminders, workflow dashboards. Everyone tracks the deadline. The filing format is well-understood. <strong>But the filing content — the classification logic, the data completeness — is a different matter entirely</strong> (see: Right Engine).</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon red">🔄</div><div class="card-title">Daily Reconciliation Breaks</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Every ops team has a rec dashboard. Breaks are visible, tracked, aged. <strong>The dangerous failures aren't the breaks that show up — they're the ones that auto-match incorrectly</strong> or the accounts that reconcile to zero because neither side booked the trade.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon red">📞</div><div class="card-title">Client Service & Query Management</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">SLA dashboards, ticket tracking, response time metrics. Heavily measured. <strong>But the measurement is "did we respond?" not "did we resolve the root cause?"</strong> A client who stops complaining isn't a satisfied client — they're a client who's started their RFP process.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon red">📈</div><div class="card-title">Performance & Attribution Reports</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Well-defined methodologies (GIPS, TWR, MWR). Third-party verification common. <strong>The risk isn't in the calculation — it's in the benchmark selection, the composite construction, and whether the methodology still matches the fund's actual strategy.</strong></div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon red">🖥️</div><div class="card-title">Platform Uptime & SLA Metrics</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">99.9% uptime! Green dashboards everywhere. <strong>But uptime ≠ availability. The system was "up" during the month-end window — but the batch took 14 hours instead of 4</strong> because someone onboarded a complex fund without a capacity review. Uptime is a vanity metric; throughput under peak load is the real measure.</div>
  </div>
</div>
```

  </div>

  <!-- ===================== CRASH SITE ===================== -->

  <div class="panel" id="panel-crash-site">
    <div class="section-header"><div class="bar rose"></div> Crash Site Analysis</div>
    <p class="section-sub">Wald studied the returning planes. But the most valuable intelligence comes from the crash site — the clients who left, the mandates you lost, the errors discovered after departure. This is the post-mortem the industry rarely conducts.</p>

```
<div class="card-grid">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon rose">🔍</div><div class="card-title">Post-Mortem Client Analytics</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>Stop heavily weighting the satisfaction surveys of your currently active, highest-AUM clients.</strong> They're the surviving planes. Conduct rigorous audits of the exact, granular reasons the last five clients left. Their reasons for departure are the untreated vulnerabilities in your current service model. The satisfaction survey tells you where the armour is working. The exit interview tells you where the fatal shots land.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon rose">⏳</div><div class="card-title">The Compound Erosion Pattern</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>A client rarely leaves due to a single catastrophic event.</strong> Departures usually follow a prolonged period of compounding minor errors — each individually forgivable, collectively fatal. The NAV was 2 bps off three times. The TA query took 48 hours twice. The month-end pack was late once. No single bullet. But the airframe was already compromised when the last one hit.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon rose">💣</div><div class="card-title">Transition Risk — The Delayed Detonation</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>When clients migrate away, their new administrator often uncovers historical inaccuracies.</strong> This exposes you to reputational damage and potential liability long after the client has left. A historical NAV error surfaced by a successor administrator is worse than one you caught yourself — because now you've lost the narrative.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon rose">📉</div><div class="card-title">The Silent RFP — When Clients Stop Complaining</div></div>
    <div class="card-body"><strong>The most dangerous signal in client relationship management is silence.</strong> A client who escalates is a client who still believes you can fix it. A client who goes quiet has moved to evaluation mode. By the time you receive the formal notification, the decision was made months ago. Your satisfaction dashboard showed green the entire time — because it measured responsiveness, not trust.</div>
  </div>
</div>
```

  </div>

  <!-- ===================== THE LESSON ===================== -->

  <div class="panel" id="panel-lesson">
    <div class="section-header"><div class="bar teal"></div> The Lesson for Fund Accounting</div>

```
<div class="wald-quote" style="border-left-color: var(--teal);">
  <p>The industry's quality framework is built around the red dots — NAV accuracy, filing deadlines, rec breaks. But the planes that never came back were hit in the data lineage, the regulatory interpretation, the integration seams — and in the culture, the institutional memory, and the human override that atrophied because nobody needed it until everyone did.</p>
  <cite>— The Wald Principle applied to Fund Administration</cite>
</div>

<div class="card-grid" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon teal">1</div><div class="card-title">Audit What You Can't See</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Build monitoring for the <strong>absence</strong> of expected events, not just the presence of errors. A missing trade feed at 08:00 is more dangerous than a broken one at 08:01. The silent failure — where nothing happens and nobody notices — is the engine hit.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon teal">2</div><div class="card-title">Test the Seams, Not the Centres</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Every platform vendor demos the NAV calculation. <strong>Ask them to demo a fund merger at month-end during a bank holiday with a timezone mismatch.</strong> The integration seams under combinatorial stress are where products actually fail.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon teal">3</div><div class="card-title">Map the Knowledge Graph</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">For every fund, ask: <strong>"If the primary accountant disappeared tomorrow, what would break?"</strong> If the answer is "everything", you've found your cockpit. Document the undocumented. Cross-train the irreplaceable. Audit the Excel graveyard.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon teal">4</div><div class="card-title">Measure Outcomes, Not Activities</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Stop measuring tickets closed and recs completed. Start measuring: <strong>How many times did a client discover an error before we did? How many near-misses were reported (and is that number suspiciously low)? What's our mean-time-to-detect for a silent data feed change?</strong></div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon teal">5</div><div class="card-title">Build the Escape Hatch</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Your data model should be <strong>yours</strong>, not your vendor's. Your regulatory logic should be auditable, versionable, and portable. If you can't export your complete fund configuration and replay a historical NAV on a different platform, you don't own your product.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon teal">6</div><div class="card-title">Stress-Test the Human Layer</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">Run a <strong>"take-back test"</strong>: can your team manually validate a complex performance fee waterfall without the platform? Measure near-miss reporting rates against complexity. If complex funds report fewer incidents than simple ones, your culture is hiding errors, not preventing them.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon teal">7</div><div class="card-title">Study the Crash Site</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">The most valuable intelligence is in the <strong>clients who left, not the ones who stayed.</strong> Conduct granular departure audits. Track compound erosion patterns. Monitor for the silent RFP signal. A historical error surfaced by a successor administrator is reputational damage with no recovery window.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-header"><div class="card-icon teal">8</div><div class="card-title">Armour Where the Holes Aren't</div></div>
    <div class="card-body">The next pound you invest in quality should go to <strong>data lineage monitoring, regulatory interpretation reviews, integration seam testing, knowledge capture, near-miss culture, and take-back capability</strong> — not another NAV tolerance check. The NAV check keeps the plane flying. Everything else keeps it from falling out of the sky.</div>
  </div>
</div>
